    {
      "kind": "content",
      "content": [
        {
          "anchor": "overview",
          "level": 2,
          "text": "Overview",
          "type": "heading"
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You illuminate your scene by attaching lights to "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " objects using their "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnnode/1408004-light"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "You set a light’s type using its "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/1522919-type"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property. Depending on a light’s type, its position and direction may affect its behavior—you control the light’s position and direction through the node that the light is attached to. The direction of a light, if applicable to its type, is along the negative z-axis of its node’s local coordinate system."
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "A light’s other properties affect how it illuminates a scene. All lights have a "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/1523627-color"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " property, which interacts with "
            },
            {
              "type": "reference",
              "isActive": true,
              "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnmaterial"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": " objects to produce the pixel colors in a rendered scene. Other properties, such as attenuation, shadowing, and spot angle, can affect the behavior of certain types of lights. "
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "paragraph",
          "inlineContent": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "text": "The number and type of lights in a scene is a key factor in SceneKit’s rendering performance. For efficient rendering, follow these tips:"
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "type": "unorderedList",
          "items": [
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "inlineHead",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "Use SceneKit lights only for dynamic light sources or lights that affect moving objects."
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " For statically lit portions of your scene, create a light map texture in an external 3D authoring tool (also known as "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "emphasis",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "baked lighting"
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": ") and apply it to objects in the scene using the "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnmaterial/1462575-multiply"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " material property."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            },
            {
              "content": [
                {
                  "type": "paragraph",
                  "inlineContent": [
                    {
                      "type": "inlineHead",
                      "inlineContent": [
                        {
                          "type": "text",
                          "text": "Minimize the number of lights on each element of the scene."
                        }
                      ]
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " You can achieve most common lighting effects using no more than three lights, and you only need a single ambient light source. SceneKit only uses up to eight light sources per node when rendering, ignoring any additional lights. If you set the "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/1524140-attenuationenddistance"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " property on a spotlight or omnidirectional light to limit its area of effect, SceneKit ignores the light (and its performance cost) when rendering objects outside that area. You can also use the "
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "reference",
                      "isActive": true,
                      "identifier": "doc://com.apple.documentation/documentation/scenekit/scnlight/1523669-categorybitmask"
                    },
                    {
                      "type": "text",
                      "text": " property to choose which nodes are illuminated by a light."
                    }
                  ]
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
